d the development of our colleges and universities ever since. He shows how Robert's rules can help faculty, administrators, and students to solve problems and overcome challenges through collaboration, disciplined thinking, trust in the facts, and honesty and fairness from all sides.At a time when people's faith in democracy and higher education has been shaken to its core, Robert's Rules of Order offers a powerful reminder of the importance of democratic norms and practices in American life and institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDemocracy and educationzUnited States. 0aParliamentary practicezUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Reference.2bisacsh  aAcademic dress.  aAcademic freedom.  aAcademic tenure.  aAdoption.  aAlexis de Tocqueville.  aAlumnus.  aAmerican Association of University Professors.  aAmerican Economic Association.  aAndrew Dickson White.  aAssociation of American Universities.  aBivalvia.  aBowdoin College.  aBrown University.  aCambridge University Press.  aCassius Dio.  aChicago Tribune.  aCivil society.  aCultural practice.  aDaniel Coit Gilman.  aDartmouth College.  aDeliberation.  aDemocracy in America.  aDemocratization.  aDionysius of Halicarnassus.  aDoctor of Philosophy.  aEdition (book).  aEducation policy.  aEducation.  aElectoral college.  aFaculty (academic staff).  aFrancis Wayland.  aFraternities and sororities.  aFraternity.  aG.I. Bill.  aGerman model.  aGraduation.  aGrand Army of the Republic.  aHarvard University.  aHenry Martyn Robert.  aHenry Rosovsky.  aHis Family.  aHoward College.  aHoward University.  aIdeology.  aIndependent Order of Odd Fellows.  aInstitution.  aIntellectual history.  aJohns Hopkins University.  aJohns Hopkins.  aKnights of Pythias.  aLand-grant un